# Written answer directly below

You may want to look at a scatter plot matrix before pursuing any further analyses using these matrices because of the presence of outliers in the data. Specifically, DOGE has a significantly weaker correlation with the rest of the crypto-currencies than the rest of the crypto-currencies have with each other. With DOGE being significanly different, numerical analysis alone might not grant a complete picture of the meaning behind the data.

Part (c)

# Written answer directly below

The covariability between Year and the president’s Approval is negative because the greater values in the Year variable mainly correspond with the lesser values of the Approval variable, and the same holds for the lesser values in the Year variable, which mainly correspond with the greater values of the Approval variable.

Part (d)

# Written answer directly below

From the scatter plot matrix above, the greatest covariability appears to be between the Approval and Margin variables. Those two variables seem to cluster along a line of best fit better than any other pair of variables.

Part (f)

# Written answer directly below

As can be seen in the correlation matrix above, the correlation between the Approval and Margin variables is the furthest from 0, making that the strongest correlation. It is also a positive correlation, while the correlation between the Year and Approval variables is negative, as is the covariability of those variables as discussed in Part (c) of this exercise.

Part (c)

# Written answer directly below
Attempting to find the correlation matrix for the penguin data stored in penguinsMatrix yields the following warning:
Warning: the standard deviation is zero


This warning comes about because there are only year values from 2007 in the penguinsMatrix. As a result, the deviation of each data point in the Year column is zero [(Xi - Xbar)^2 = (2007 - 2007)^2 = 0^2 = 0 for all datapoints]. Consequently, the sum of squares will also be zero, and therefore standard deviation will be calculated as (0/30-1), which is also zero. This is why the warning comes about, and the consequence of having zero as a standard deviation is that for each of the correlations involving year, the covariability of some arbitrary variable and the Year variable will be divided by product of the standard deviation of that arbitrary variable and the standard deviation of the Year variable, which is zero. Dividing by zero is undefined, and therefore the correlation matrix can only populate the correlations involving the Year variable with “NA”.

Part (f)

# Written answer directly below

The differences between these two correlation matricies are minimal to the point of being undetectable to my eye, but some very slight differences can be noticed when viewing the two correlation plots. Take the correlation between the Subclass variable and the Quality variable. In the pairwise complete correlation plot, that square is slightly larger and darker than the corresponding square in the complete correlation plot. The opposite pattern can be noticed with the Subclass variable and the Built variable, as well as the Subclass variable and the Remodel variable. In each of those cases, the pairwise complete correlation plot, that square is slightly smaller and lighter than the corresponding square in the complete correlation plot.
